      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think i get the gist. but i've seen people call it \"spooky action at a distance\" which sounds kind of weird... why do they call it spooky? is there something actually \"unexplained\" about how it works or is it just a metaphor?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of entanglement. He felt that it was \"spooky\" because it seemed to defy the classical idea of causality, where cause and effect are closely tied by space and time. In the case of entanglement, the effect on one particle seems to happen instantly, regardless of the distance between the particles, which is hard to wrap your head around. It's a bit like a \"mysterious\" or \"unusual\" phenomenon, but it's not necessarily \"unexplained\" in the sense that the laws of physics haven't been rewritten. It's more like a challenge to our classical understanding of the world.",
